        <h2>5. PlanSwift — Best for framing takeoffs</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> ~$1,749/yr (~$146/mo)</p>

        <p>PlanSwift is a digital plan takeoff tool, not a full PM platform. For framing contractors who spend significant time counting pieces and measuring linear footage from blueprints, PlanSwift dramatically speeds up the estimating process. You load a PDF set of drawings, draw your takeoff digitally, and the software calculates quantities automatically.</p>

        <p>Most useful for framing contractors doing complex commercial work or custom residential where accurate lumber counts are critical to profitability. Use this alongside a PM platform like Contractor Foreman or JobTread.</p>

        <h2>What framing contractors actually need in software</h2>

        <h3>Bid tracking</h3>
        <p>As a sub, you need to track which GCs sent you bid requests, what you quoted, whether you won or lost, and why. Even a simple CRM function for this saves bids from slipping through the cracks. Contractor Foreman includes this; Jobber handles it through estimates.</p>

        <h3>Crew scheduling across concurrent jobs</h3>
        <p>Framing crews often work on multiple houses in sequence during production housing phases. You need visibility into which crew is where, what's scheduled next, and whether a delay on one job cascades into another. Contractor Foreman and Jobber both handle multi-job scheduling.</p>

        <h3>Lumber and material tracking</h3>
        <p>Lumber prices fluctuate significantly. Your estimate might have been based on prices from three months ago. Software that tracks actual material costs against estimated costs catches price variance early — before it destroys your margin.</p>

        <h3>Labor productivity tracking</h3>
        <p>The real value of time tracking is benchmarking: how many hours per 1,000 square feet of framing does your crew average? Over time, this data lets you price more accurately and spot when a job is trending toward a loss before it's too late.</p>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>I'm a framing sub — do I need software or just QuickBooks?</h3>
        <p>QuickBooks handles your accounting but doesn't help you manage jobs in the field or bid work accurately. The combination that works best: QuickBooks for accounting + Contractor Foreman or Jobber for job management. They connect to QuickBooks directly, so you're not entering data twice.</p>

        <h3>Can I use the GC's Buildertrend account instead of buying my own?</h3>
        <p>Yes — GCs can add subs to Buildertrend at no cost to the sub. You'd get access to job documents, schedules, and communications for jobs that GC assigns to you. This doesn't replace your own system for managing your business (bidding, payroll, etc.) but reduces what you need to buy.</p>

        <h3>How do I track lumber delivery against a job?</h3>
        <p>Create a purchase order in your PM software tied to the specific job. When lumber is delivered, verify the PO quantities and mark it received. This creates a paper trail for job costs and helps you identify waste or theft over time.</p>

